1
00:00:00,220 --> 00:00:01,980
<i>[CLOCK TICKING]</i>

2
00:00:04,700 --> 00:00:06,300
[#]

3
00:00:20,100 --> 00:00:21,660
<i>[MAN PANTING]</i>

4
00:00:57,260 --> 00:00:59,020
<i>[MAN PANTING]</i>

5
00:01:30,900 --> 00:01:34,660
<i>MAN: Sometimes I admit to
myself that it's possible</i>

6
00:01:34,660 --> 00:01:37,500
<i>I will never be able
to finish my life's work.</i>

7
00:01:41,460 --> 00:01:43,260
<i>My one and only book.</i>

8
00:01:45,540 --> 00:01:48,420
<i>And that in the end,
without her...</i>

9
00:01:51,660 --> 00:01:53,220
[#]

10
00:01:54,620 --> 00:01:57,340
<i>...there will be nothing.</i>

11
00:01:57,340 --> 00:01:58,980
<i>And I will die alone.</i>

12
00:02:02,380 --> 00:02:04,220
[CRYING]

13
00:02:15,380 --> 00:02:16,900
<i>What are you doing here,
Coane Dominic?</i>

14
00:02:19,820 --> 00:02:22,500
I have a migraine.

15
00:02:22,500 --> 00:02:24,060
I thought a walk might help.

16
00:02:24,060 --> 00:02:26,740
But in your pajamas
on Christmas Eve?

17
00:02:26,740 --> 00:02:28,220
Don't catch cold. Look.

18
00:02:30,860 --> 00:02:33,180
At the first opportunity,
I'll...

19
00:02:35,900 --> 00:02:37,980
What do you do
at the first opportunity?

20
00:02:40,140 --> 00:02:43,260
DOMINIC: At the first
opportunity, I have to-- I have--

21
00:02:43,260 --> 00:02:45,020
It's in the drawer.

22
00:02:45,020 --> 00:02:47,940
I-- I have saved--
I saved it for--

23
00:02:47,940 --> 00:02:51,700
At the first opportunity,
I will open the blue envelope.

24
00:02:53,380 --> 00:02:57,140
Not here in Piatra Neamt
where everyone knows me,

25
00:02:57,140 --> 00:02:58,260
but somewhere far away.

26
00:03:02,780 --> 00:03:04,820
Bucharest perhaps.

27
00:03:04,820 --> 00:03:05,820
At Easter.

28
00:03:08,220 --> 00:03:10,100
[#]

29
00:04:13,820 --> 00:04:14,780
[BELL TOLLING]

30
00:04:14,780 --> 00:04:16,620
[HORN HONKING]

31
00:04:18,340 --> 00:04:19,260
[THUNDER CRASHES]

32
00:04:28,220 --> 00:04:29,460
<i>Universul.</i>

33
00:04:30,740 --> 00:04:32,140
<i>Universul.</i>

34
00:04:40,540 --> 00:04:45,780
<i>BOY: Special Easter
edition. Universul.</i>

35
00:04:45,780 --> 00:04:48,300
War clouds over Romania.

36
00:04:48,300 --> 00:04:49,420
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

37
00:04:49,420 --> 00:04:50,700
WOMAN:
Oh, it's pouring.

38
00:05:02,380 --> 00:05:04,300
<i>Universul.</i>

39
00:05:16,740 --> 00:05:18,420
WOMAN: He was struck by lightning.

40
00:05:18,420 --> 00:05:19,420
WOMAN 2:
Call an ambulance.

41
00:05:21,180 --> 00:05:23,900
WOMAN 3:
Call for some help.

42
00:05:23,900 --> 00:05:26,340
WOMAN 4: Look, who knows
what sins he has committed

43
00:05:26,340 --> 00:05:27,980
that God would strike him
on Easter.

44
00:05:27,980 --> 00:05:33,180
They say whoever dies during
Easter goes straight to heaven.

45
00:05:36,060 --> 00:05:37,980
[#]

46
00:05:39,900 --> 00:05:41,340
<i>WOMAN:
Dominic.</i>

47
00:05:47,260 --> 00:05:49,540
DOMINIC:
Oh...

48
00:05:49,540 --> 00:05:52,860
<i>I will wish you.
You know what I mean. I mean...</i>

49
00:05:54,660 --> 00:05:57,660
<i>I will love you
until the day I die.</i>

50
00:06:08,540 --> 00:06:12,260
MAN:
The eye seems intact,

51
00:06:12,260 --> 00:06:16,380
but I don't know
if he is blind or not.

52
00:06:16,380 --> 00:06:18,940
I don't even know
if he's conscious,

53
00:06:18,940 --> 00:06:24,860
if he hears or
if he understands what he hears.

54
00:06:24,860 --> 00:06:30,060
If you understand what I say,
squeeze my finger.

55
00:06:42,060 --> 00:06:44,460
I'm Dr. Roman Stanciulescu.

56
00:06:44,460 --> 00:06:46,780
I'm here to help you.

57
00:06:49,780 --> 00:06:51,300
Good.

58
00:06:51,300 --> 00:06:53,660
We wish to find out
your age.

59
00:06:53,660 --> 00:06:57,740
For every 10 years,
squeeze my finger once.

60
00:07:02,140 --> 00:07:02,940
Ten.

61
00:07:05,900 --> 00:07:07,620
Twenty.
Twenty.

62
00:07:09,100 --> 00:07:10,300
Thirty.

63
00:07:13,020 --> 00:07:14,420
Forty.
Forty.

64
00:07:15,900 --> 00:07:17,060
Fifty.
Fifty.

65
00:07:18,940 --> 00:07:20,660
Sixty.
Sixty.

66
00:07:23,260 --> 00:07:25,460
Seventy.
WOMAN: Seventy.

67
00:07:27,260 --> 00:07:28,380
Seventy years old.

68
00:07:30,020 --> 00:07:33,860
MAN: Seventy. I would
have thought less.

69
00:07:33,860 --> 00:07:38,460
Well, in this larval state,

70
00:07:38,460 --> 00:07:40,180
it's hard to estimate.

71
00:07:45,900 --> 00:07:47,380
[#]

72
00:07:55,100 --> 00:07:57,620
<i>WOMAN: I've never
met anyone like you.</i>

73
00:07:57,620 --> 00:08:00,900
<i>You want to know
absolutely everything.</i>

74
00:08:00,900 --> 00:08:03,300
Laura, try to imagine

75
00:08:03,300 --> 00:08:05,980
conceiving a passion
for something,

76
00:08:05,980 --> 00:08:08,380
having one desire,
dedicating your life to it

77
00:08:08,380 --> 00:08:09,980
and then failing.

78
00:08:09,980 --> 00:08:11,100
I am 26.

79
00:08:11,100 --> 00:08:12,740
I have no accomplishments,

80
00:08:12,740 --> 00:08:14,940
I've made no discoveries.

81
00:08:14,940 --> 00:08:16,500
I'm a failure.

82
00:08:16,500 --> 00:08:18,340
ROMAN:
Do you have a wife?

83
00:08:19,780 --> 00:08:21,220
MAN: No.
WOMAN: - No.

84
00:08:21,220 --> 00:08:22,700
MAN:
Nephew?

85
00:08:25,580 --> 00:08:27,500
Yes.
- Nephew.

86
00:08:27,500 --> 00:08:28,860
Nephew.
- Do you want us

87
00:08:28,860 --> 00:08:31,700
to inform your nephew
about your condition?

88
00:08:31,700 --> 00:08:33,700
No.

89
00:08:33,700 --> 00:08:37,700
Let us know the first letter
of your name. Continue.

90
00:08:37,700 --> 00:08:39,940
I am going to say
the alphabet.

91
00:08:39,940 --> 00:08:46,260
A, B, C, D...

92
00:08:46,260 --> 00:08:47,940
D.
- D.

93
00:08:47,940 --> 00:08:51,740
He doesn't live
in Bucharest.

94
00:08:51,740 --> 00:08:55,740
He has only one relative,
a distant one,

95
00:08:55,740 --> 00:08:58,380
and he has no wife.

96
00:08:58,380 --> 00:08:59,500
Thank you.

97
00:09:02,900 --> 00:09:06,420
He'll accept any test,

98
00:09:06,420 --> 00:09:09,420
no matter how dangerous
or painful,

99
00:09:09,420 --> 00:09:12,940
to verify whether
the optic nerve was damaged.

100
00:09:16,020 --> 00:09:17,260
That's interesting.

101
00:09:18,100 --> 00:09:19,940
[#]

102
00:09:28,060 --> 00:09:30,100
[GIGGLING]

103
00:09:30,100 --> 00:09:32,140
How old did you say he was?

104
00:09:32,140 --> 00:09:33,500
Seventy.

105
00:09:33,500 --> 00:09:35,180
He's hiding his age.

106
00:09:35,180 --> 00:09:38,020
He's a young man
in the prime of his life.

107
00:09:42,460 --> 00:09:45,180
MAN:
I didn't come here...

108
00:09:45,180 --> 00:09:47,740
I came here for an education.
MAN 2: - Come.

109
00:09:47,740 --> 00:09:49,860
What did you think
about the lecture?

110
00:09:49,860 --> 00:09:51,660
MAN: Professor Matei
is getting senile.

111
00:09:51,660 --> 00:09:54,300
He told us the same thing
three or four times.

112
00:09:54,300 --> 00:09:56,620
MAN 2: I didn't
notice. I was asleep.

113
00:09:56,620 --> 00:09:58,340
Let's go get
something to eat.

114
00:10:01,340 --> 00:10:02,820
<i>DOMINIC:
Is it true?</i>

115
00:10:06,020 --> 00:10:08,700
<i>LAURA:
Failure, success.</i>

116
00:10:08,700 --> 00:10:10,620
<i>Such extremes, Dominic.</i>

117
00:10:10,620 --> 00:10:12,940
You yourself taught me
about Chandrakirti.

118
00:10:12,940 --> 00:10:16,260
The concept of tetralemma logic,
the four possibilities.

119
00:10:16,260 --> 00:10:19,420
What you say is so,
or it is not so,

120
00:10:19,420 --> 00:10:21,940
it's also so
and not so combined, heh,

121
00:10:21,940 --> 00:10:24,580
or it's neither so
nor not so combined.

122
00:10:24,580 --> 00:10:25,980
<i>[GASPS] DOMINIC: You know,</i>

123
00:10:25,980 --> 00:10:27,260
<i>I've never told you this,</i>

124
00:10:27,260 --> 00:10:29,460
<i>but Dr. Chavannes' lecture
in Paris...</i>

125
00:10:29,460 --> 00:10:30,580
I waited to see him.

126
00:10:30,580 --> 00:10:34,540
I was hoping that he would
accept me as a student.

127
00:10:34,540 --> 00:10:38,540
And he told me that if I didn't
master Chinese, Sanskrit,

128
00:10:38,540 --> 00:10:42,140
Tibetan and Japanese,

129
00:10:42,140 --> 00:10:44,940
I would never become
a great Orientalist.

130
00:10:44,940 --> 00:10:46,140
But didn't you tell him

131
00:10:46,140 --> 00:10:48,060
you wanted to study
only the Chinese language?

132
00:10:48,060 --> 00:10:49,340
I did.

133
00:10:49,340 --> 00:10:51,620
<i>I told him that
I'd been studying Chinese</i>

134
00:10:51,620 --> 00:10:53,020
<i>for six months,
six hours a day.</i>

135
00:10:53,020 --> 00:10:54,780
<i>He stepped up
to the blackboard.</i>

136
00:10:54,780 --> 00:10:57,300
<i>He wrote
some 20 characters on it,</i>

137
00:10:57,300 --> 00:10:58,620
<i>and he asked me
to pronounce them</i>

138
00:10:58,620 --> 00:11:01,620
<i>one by one
and then translate the passage.</i>

139
00:11:01,620 --> 00:11:04,380
<i>In order to master Chinese,</i>

140
00:11:04,380 --> 00:11:07,380
<i>one must have
the memory of Mandarin.</i>

141
00:11:07,380 --> 00:11:11,300
<i>Photographic memory.</i>

142
00:11:11,300 --> 00:11:13,180
<i>A memory of a Mandarin.</i>

143
00:11:14,460 --> 00:11:16,180
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

144
00:11:16,180 --> 00:11:18,940
MAN: I remember hearing
about another case,

145
00:11:18,940 --> 00:11:21,020
a priest hit by lightning.

146
00:11:21,020 --> 00:11:22,900
Burned over his whole body

147
00:11:22,900 --> 00:11:25,260
and would survive
many years afterwards.

148
00:11:25,260 --> 00:11:27,420
True, he was left
blind and mute,

149
00:11:27,420 --> 00:11:29,220
as our man is also probably.

150
00:11:29,220 --> 00:11:32,740
Don't talk so loud.
Maybe he can hear you.

151
00:11:32,740 --> 00:11:34,660
I want him to hear me.

152
00:11:34,660 --> 00:11:37,980
Let's see how he'll react.
Maybe he isn't mute at all.

153
00:11:37,980 --> 00:11:39,580
No!
[YELPS]

154
00:11:39,580 --> 00:11:44,700
Not mute! Not mute!

155
00:11:44,700 --> 00:11:47,140
Try to pronounce any word,
anything.

156
00:11:50,180 --> 00:11:55,100
Blue envelope.

157
00:11:55,100 --> 00:11:57,220
WOMAN:
Blue envelope.

158
00:11:57,220 --> 00:11:58,380
Envelope...

159
00:11:58,380 --> 00:12:00,860
[GROANING]

160
00:12:00,860 --> 00:12:02,980
MAN: The teeth,
they're barely holding.

161
00:12:02,980 --> 00:12:05,540
Call the dentist right now
and see if the x-rays are ready.

162
00:12:13,660 --> 00:12:14,820
What's next?

163
00:12:14,820 --> 00:12:17,460
"Romania may be forced
to negotiate with Hitler."

164
00:12:17,460 --> 00:12:20,180
France is abandoning us
to the Nazis.

165
00:12:20,180 --> 00:12:22,380
He is right.

166
00:12:22,380 --> 00:12:23,900
His x-rays have come in.

167
00:12:23,900 --> 00:12:25,780
You really should
take a look at them.

168
00:12:25,780 --> 00:12:31,020
The roots are healthy, but they
are being pushed up by new ones.

169
00:12:34,780 --> 00:12:37,220
So we feel you're out
of danger.

170
00:12:39,740 --> 00:12:42,300
Only now do you begin
to become an interesting case.

171
00:12:42,300 --> 00:12:44,620
You understand why,
don't you?

172
00:12:44,620 --> 00:12:46,380
The way the lightning
struck you,

173
00:12:46,380 --> 00:12:48,620
you had to have been killed
on the spot,

174
00:12:48,620 --> 00:12:52,460
or else to have died
of asphyxiation.

175
00:12:52,460 --> 00:12:55,860
At best you'd
be left paralyzed,

176
00:12:58,220 --> 00:13:00,500
mute or blind.

177
00:13:04,380 --> 00:13:07,940
You are lucky,
I'll give you that.

178
00:13:10,700 --> 00:13:12,100
Yes.

179
00:13:12,100 --> 00:13:15,300
We had ordered a set of dentures
to allow you to eat

180
00:13:15,300 --> 00:13:18,780
and above all,
to speak normally.

181
00:13:18,780 --> 00:13:21,900
But the x-rays show
that, uh,

182
00:13:21,900 --> 00:13:27,060
a new set of teeth
are ready to appear.

183
00:13:27,060 --> 00:13:29,060
It's impossible.

184
00:13:29,060 --> 00:13:32,020
Yes. It's simply impossible.

185
00:13:33,660 --> 00:13:36,340
And yet the x-rays are clear.

186
00:13:38,300 --> 00:13:39,900
You are getting new teeth.

187
00:13:41,860 --> 00:13:45,180
This is no longer a case
of a living dead man,

188
00:13:45,180 --> 00:13:46,900
but of something else.

189
00:13:46,900 --> 00:13:50,140
What, exactly,

190
00:13:50,140 --> 00:13:51,900
we still don't know.

191
00:13:51,900 --> 00:13:55,180
Your recovery is amazing.

192
00:13:56,700 --> 00:13:59,420
[MOANING]

193
00:13:59,420 --> 00:14:01,540
I don't want to tire you out.

194
00:14:01,540 --> 00:14:03,860
Get some rest.
I'll be back tomorrow.

195
00:14:07,820 --> 00:14:10,420
[BELLS TOLLING]

196
00:14:10,420 --> 00:14:12,900
News stories
and feature articles

197
00:14:12,900 --> 00:14:15,820
are starting to appear
in different papers,

198
00:14:15,820 --> 00:14:18,860
the majority of them absurd,
ridiculous.

199
00:14:22,060 --> 00:14:23,620
What are you doing?

200
00:14:33,020 --> 00:14:34,380
New teeth!

201
00:14:36,140 --> 00:14:40,780
But you must help us
understand this.

202
00:14:40,780 --> 00:14:43,860
We have to know more about you,
who you are,

203
00:14:43,860 --> 00:14:45,100
what your profession is.

204
00:14:45,100 --> 00:14:47,740
What's your real age?

205
00:14:47,740 --> 00:14:50,300
Please cooperate
a little more.

206
00:14:52,620 --> 00:14:54,980
Were you so stubborn
when you were young?

207
00:14:57,820 --> 00:14:59,540
Always.

208
00:14:59,540 --> 00:15:02,180
<i>MAN: What is this you
insist on writing, young man?</i>

209
00:15:02,180 --> 00:15:06,940
Well, I've almost finished
with antiquity, the Middle Ages.

210
00:15:06,940 --> 00:15:11,100
But the most exciting part,
the origins.

211
00:15:11,100 --> 00:15:13,020
The origins of language, of--

212
00:15:13,020 --> 00:15:14,820
But when will
you finish it, Dominic?

213
00:15:14,820 --> 00:15:17,220
He needs 10 lifetimes
to do it all.

214
00:15:17,220 --> 00:15:19,940
DOMINIC: The origins of
language, human consciousness,

215
00:15:19,940 --> 00:15:21,740
even the idea
of time itself.

216
00:15:21,740 --> 00:15:24,420
This would call for years
of research.

217
00:15:24,420 --> 00:15:26,900
And what with the inexperience
of our provincial...

218
00:15:26,900 --> 00:15:28,940
[BELLS TOLLING]
...librarians.

219
00:15:28,940 --> 00:15:31,300
I'm terribly sorry,
professor.

220
00:15:32,860 --> 00:15:36,980
I have an appointment.
I really must run.

221
00:15:36,980 --> 00:15:39,140
[#]

222
00:15:39,140 --> 00:15:42,700
He's brilliant. Brilliant. But--

223
00:15:44,700 --> 00:15:48,660
Laura, I'm so sorry.
I completely forgot.

224
00:15:48,660 --> 00:15:50,300
We have to talk,
Dominic.

225
00:15:50,300 --> 00:15:51,860
It's very important
for both of us,

226
00:15:51,860 --> 00:15:53,980
and I can't hide it
any longer.

227
00:15:53,980 --> 00:15:55,580
Of course.

228
00:15:55,580 --> 00:15:57,980
It's snowing. Should we go
to the Café Select?

229
00:15:57,980 --> 00:16:02,260
No. And please don't interrupt.
It's not what you think.

230
00:16:11,740 --> 00:16:15,060
I feel that you aren't mine,

231
00:16:15,060 --> 00:16:17,180
that you are never here with me.

232
00:16:17,180 --> 00:16:20,300
That you--
That you live in another time.

233
00:16:22,660 --> 00:16:24,460
I'm not thinking
of your research,

234
00:16:24,460 --> 00:16:27,220
which in spite of what
you believe, does interest me.

235
00:16:27,220 --> 00:16:29,300
I wanted to help you
with that.

236
00:16:29,300 --> 00:16:32,420
But you keep yourself shut away
in an alien world,

237
00:16:32,420 --> 00:16:33,820
one I can't enter.

238
00:16:36,060 --> 00:16:38,740
So for my sake and for yours,

239
00:16:38,740 --> 00:16:41,540
we should break
our engagement and separate.

240
00:16:41,540 --> 00:16:43,060
No.

241
00:16:43,060 --> 00:16:44,060
Laura, no.

242
00:16:44,060 --> 00:16:46,740
We are still young.

243
00:16:46,740 --> 00:16:48,820
We both love life.

244
00:16:51,900 --> 00:16:54,380
You will have more time
for your research.

245
00:16:56,660 --> 00:16:57,540
You'll see later.

246
00:16:59,580 --> 00:17:01,420
[#]

247
00:17:25,740 --> 00:17:27,620
[GROANING]

248
00:17:31,740 --> 00:17:33,140
Tell the professor
what he wants to know.

249
00:17:35,340 --> 00:17:37,420
Tell him you need
a new identity.

250
00:17:45,100 --> 00:17:47,700
All right, you can go.
I'll be here all afternoon.

251
00:17:56,860 --> 00:17:58,780
I understand
that you are willing

252
00:17:58,780 --> 00:18:00,620
to speak to me candidly.

253
00:18:03,260 --> 00:18:05,460
You don't have to make
a great effort.

254
00:18:05,460 --> 00:18:08,700
The words you cannot pronounce,
you can write.

255
00:18:15,180 --> 00:18:16,340
My name...

256
00:18:18,140 --> 00:18:20,180
is Dominic Matei.

257
00:18:22,700 --> 00:18:25,820
On January the 8th...

258
00:18:25,820 --> 00:18:28,340
